      {
        "id": 1,
        "lineId": 1,
        "beatId": 2,
        "bookId": null,
        "positionWithinLine": 0,
        "positionInBeat": 0,
        "title": "Climax Hook",
        "description": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "--- Add Your Details Above This Line ---"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Beginning of Act 1:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "In Media Res is Latin for Into the Middle, a story structure that starts in the middle of the action before circling back to the beginning.",
                "italic": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Unlike traditional story structures, this one drops the reader into the middle of the story's Climax and offers tantalizing details to hook the reader before returning to the Exposition of the story. As such, it is important to have the beginning, middle, and end of the story planned before attempting this format. The opening scene must be attention-grabbing and provoke curiosity, driving the reader to wonder not only how the story got to this point but how it can be resolved."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bulleted-list",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Write an amazing first line, something that catches attention and immediatly intrigues."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Do not present the entirety of the Climax, but rather enter a scene in progress and leave before its resolution."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "The scene must be pivotal to the story – for example, consider having the Protagonist in a life-or-death situation or doing something unusual like hiding in the wheel hub of an airplane. "
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Make the reader ask: What's going on here? Who are the characters? Where are we? How did we get here? What will happen next?"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Remember, when starting in the middle of the action, the reader has very little context, so it is essential to make the first scene attention-grabbing and full of emotion."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Breakdown:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bulleted-list",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Act 1 makes up the first 25% of the story."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Climax Hook should take approximately 5% - 10% of the story."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
